{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658924"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:58:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:58:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20836"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20836"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96377"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13711"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20836"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79026"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"11598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12661"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33013"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33014"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96377"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a hamartoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A developmental cyst lined by epithelium","A disorganized mass of cells indigenous to the site","A malignant tumour with metastatic potential","An inflammatory mass resulting from chronic infection","A collection of heterotopic tissue from another site"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Edisorganized mass of cells indigenous to the site\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes a hamartoma. Hamartomas are composed of mature tissue elements that are normally found at that anatomical site but are arranged in a disorganized fashion. While previously considered developmental malformations, most hamartomas have been found to contain clonal chromosomal aberrations acquired through somatic mutations, which supports their classification as benign neoplasms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA malignant tumour with metastatic potential\u003C/strong\u003E - Hamartomas are benign growths without malignant or metastatic potential.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAn inflammatory mass resulting from chronic infection\u003C/strong\u003E - Hamartomas are not inflammatory in nature but are neoplastic growths.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA developmental cyst lined by epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E - While developmental in origin, hamartomas are solid masses of disorganized tissue rather than cystic structures.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA collection of heterotopic tissue from another site\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a choristoma, where normal tissue is found in an abnormal location. In contrast, hamartomas contain tissue elements that are normal for that site but arranged abnormally.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of hamartomas include pulmonary hamartomas, which contain disorganized cartilage, fat, and respiratory epithelium, and Peutz-Jeghers polyps in the intestine, which contain disorganized smooth muscle and intestinal epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A hamartoma is a disorganized mass composed of cells indigenous to the involved tissue.","Hamartomas were previously thought to be developmental malformations but are now considered benign neoplasms based on clonal chromosomal aberrations.","Hamartomas contain mature tissue elements normally found at that anatomical site but arranged in a disorganized fashion."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; 269-270."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79026"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20836"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79026"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T08:48:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T08:49:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13711"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96377"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neoplasia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":6,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11598"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Nomenclature","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12661"},"attributes":{"emoji":""